          "padding": [
            0,
            80
          ],
          "alignItems": "center",
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "frame",
              "id": "exeX2",
              "name": "ArticleInner",
              "width": 720,
              "layout": "vertical",
              "gap": 32,
              "padding": [
                48,
                0,
                64,
                0
              ],
              "children": [
                {
                  "type": "frame",
                  "id": "7Nv5P",
                  "name": "Meta",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "gap": 12,
                  "alignItems": "center",
                  "children": [
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "rpevZ",
                      "name": "dDate",
                      "fill": "$foreground-tertiary",
                      "content": "March 15, 2026",
                      "fontFamily": "Geist Mono",
                      "fontSize": 13,
                      "fontWeight": "500"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "ellipse",
                      "id": "HalEr",
                      "name": "dDot",
                      "fill": "$foreground-tertiary",
                      "width": 3,
                      "height": 3
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "Sds1U",
                      "name": "dReadTime",
                      "fill": "$foreground-tertiary",
                      "content": "5 min read",
                      "fontFamily": "Geist Mono",
                      "fontSize": 13,
                      "fontWeight": "500"
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "Dapgs",
                  "name": "articleTitle",
                  "fill": "$foreground-primary",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Building Scalable Systems with Clean Architecture",
                  "lineHeight": 1.2,
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 42,
                  "fontWeight": "800",
                  "letterSpacing": -1
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "r5XNA",
                  "name": "articleAbstract",
                  "fill": "$foreground-secondary",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "An exploration of how clean architecture principles help build maintainable, testable software systems that stand the test of time. We'll examine the key patterns and practices that separate robust codebases from fragile ones.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.7,
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 18,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "rectangle",
                  "id": "Nb8fG",
                  "name": "dDivider",
                  "fill": "$border-subtle",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "height": 1
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "0LwTE",
                  "name": "bodyP1",
                  "fill": "$foreground-primary",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Software architecture is the foundation upon which all code is built. Without a clear architectural vision, projects inevitably devolve into tangled dependency graphs that resist change and breed bugs. Clean Architecture, as popularized by Robert C. Martin, offers a disciplined approach to organizing code that keeps business logic at the center while pushing infrastructure concerns to the edges.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.8,
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 17,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "Yd7Rv",
                  "name": "bodyH2",
                  "fill": "$foreground-primary",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "The Dependency Rule",
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 28,
                  "fontWeight": "700",
                  "letterSpacing": -0.5
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "kObKj",
                  "name": "bodyP2",
                  "fill": "$foreground-primary",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "The fundamental rule of Clean Architecture is simple: source code dependencies must point inward. Nothing in an inner circle can know anything about something in an outer circle. This means that your business rules don't know about the database, the UI, or any external framework. They exist in pure isolation, making them trivially testable and infinitely portable.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.8,
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 17,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "glLT4",
                  "name": "bodyP3",
                  "fill": "$foreground-primary",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "In practice, this translates to a project structure where your domain entities and use cases live in the innermost layer. They define interfaces (ports) that outer layers implement (adapters). Your API controllers, database repositories, and message handlers all live in the outer layer, depending inward toward the core — never the reverse.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.8,
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 17,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "d5VxE",
                  "name": "bodyH2b",
                  "fill": "$foreground-primary",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Practical Implementation in .NET",
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 28,
                  "fontWeight": "700",
                  "letterSpacing": -0.5
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "vnQCv",
                  "name": "bodyP4",
                  "fill": "$foreground-primary",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "In a .NET solution, this typically manifests as separate projects: Domain (entities, value objects), Application (use cases, interfaces), Infrastructure (EF Core, external services), and API (controllers, middleware). MediatR serves as the messaging backbone, routing commands and queries to their handlers without tight coupling between layers.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.8,
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 17,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "frame",
                  "id": "C5oNh",
                  "name": "codeBlock",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "fill": "$surface-elevated",
                  "cornerRadius": 8,
                  "stroke": {
                    "thickness": 1,
                    "fill": "$border-subtle"
                  },
                  "layout": "vertical",
                  "padding": 24,
                  "children": [
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "1HS3B",
                      "name": "dCode",
                      "fill": "$foreground-primary",
                      "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                      "width": "fill_container",
                      "content": "public class CreatePostHandler\n    : IRequestHandler<CreatePost, PostDto>\n{\n    private readonly IBlogDbContext _context;\n\n    public async Task<PostDto> Handle(\n        CreatePost request,\n        CancellationToken ct)\n    {\n        var post = new Post(request.Title);\n        _context.Posts.Add(post);\n        await _context.SaveChangesAsync(ct);\n        return post.ToDto();\n    }\n}",
                      "lineHeight": 1.6,
                      "fontFamily": "Geist Mono",
                      "fontSize": 14,
                      "fontWeight": "normal"
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "O1TBw",
                  "name": "bodyP5",
                  "fill": "$foreground-primary",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "The key insight is that this structure makes testing a joy rather than a chore. Your handlers can be tested in complete isolation — no database, no HTTP context, no external dependencies. Mock the interface, call the handler, assert the result. Fast, reliable, deterministic.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.8,
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 17,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "pRjMy",
                  "name": "bodyH2c",
                  "fill": "$foreground-primary",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Conclusion",
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 28,
                  "fontWeight": "700",
                  "letterSpacing": -0.5
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "Y5nep",
                  "name": "bodyP6",
                  "fill": "$foreground-primary",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Clean Architecture isn't a silver bullet, but it's one of the most effective tools for building systems that survive contact with changing requirements. Start with the dependency rule, build outward, and let your domain drive the design.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.8,
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 17,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "rectangle",
                  "id": "G8MSb",
                  "name": "dDivider2",
                  "fill": "$border-subtle",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "height": 1
                },
